  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the common hall",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] i. e. “the Prætorium” (Mark), which meant originally (1) the general’s tent; (2) it was then used for the residence of the governor or prince, cp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 23:35",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; (3) then for an official Roman villa or country house; (4) barracks especially for the Prætorian guard; (5) the Prætorian guard itself (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Php 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The second meaning (2) is to be preferred here.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "band",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Greek ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "speira",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the thirtieth part of a Roman legion consisting of two centuries.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "27–30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Jesus is mocked by the Roman Soldiers",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "St Luke, who records the mockery of Herod’s soldiers, perhaps as St Paul’s companion in the Prætorium at Rome makes no mention of this stain on the Roman soldiery.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 27:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ὅλην τὴν σπεῖραν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the whole band",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") sc. even those soldiers who ought not then to have been present, and had not been so previously.[1191]—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΣΠΕῖΡΑΝ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "band",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Lat. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "spiram",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Elsewhere the Greeks are wont to put a simple for the Latin ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " before a consonant, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Πιλάτος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", not ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΠΕΙΛΆΤΟς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; they wrote, however, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΣΠΕῖΡΑ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", because it is thus nearest to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΠΕῖΡΑ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "an attempt;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "σπεῖρω",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to sow",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc.; to the sound of which they were accustomed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "[1191] Hereby the delivery of the Saviour into the hands of the sinful heathen was consummated.—B. H. E., p. 220.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Bengel here alludes to our Lord’s words in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 20:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 26:45",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—(I. B.)",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verses 27-30.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Jesus mocked by the soldiers.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Mark 15:16-19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 19:2, 3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 27.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The soldiers of the governor.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " The brutal soldiers, far from feeling compassion for the meek Sufferer, take a fiendish pleasure in torturing and insulting him. They fling upon his bleeding body his upper garments, and take him ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "into the common hall",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "πραιτώριον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "the Praetorium",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This name was applied to the dwelling house of the provincial governor, and here refers to the open court of the building, outside which the preceding events had taken place (see on ver. 2). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The whole band",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σπεῖραν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), which usually signifies \"a cohort\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 10:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), but sometimes only a maniple, which was a third part of the same (Polybius, 11:23:1). This is probably what is meant here, as they would not denude the barracks of all its occupants, who consisted of one cohort of about six hundred men (Josephus, 'Bell. Jud.,' 2:15. 6). The soldiers summoned their comrades on guard at the palace or in the Tower of Antonia to come and join in the cruel sport. \"The devil was then entering in fury into the hearts of all. For indeed they made a pleasure of their insults against him, being a savage and a worthless set\" (Chrysostom, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "in loc.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Matthew 27:27",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]